[White "#1"]
[Black "5...b6 French"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598781"]

1. e4 e6 {The French Defence is the 3rd most popular opening against 1. e4. When 
I think about the King's Indian Attack - KIA - after 1. e4, it is this opening 
that comes into my mind. The great Bobby Fischer played a few games vs that 
tough-to-crack defence scoring remarkable victories. I decided that it is worth 
starting with 1... e6 so here we go.} 2. d3 $1 ({Of course, if you want to play 
the KIA, you need to start with this move.} 2. g3 $6 d5 {and White doesn't have 
time for} 3. d3 {due to} 3... dxe4 {and Black will get Queens off the board - it 
is not what we want.}) d5 {A 'French' move. 2... c5 would transpose to the Qe2 
vs e6 Sicilian lines *#8* or *#9*.} 3. Nd2 ({Just in time. Now, if Black decides 
to go for} 3. Nd2 3... dxe4 {we can safely play} 4. dxe4 {and the Knight on d2 
is very useful.}) c5 4. Ngf3 {White develops the Knight on the most natural 
square and will play g2-g3 next.} Nc6 (4... Bd6 5. g3 Nc6) {transposes to the 
*4... Nc6 5. g3 Bd6* line.} 5. g3 b6 6. Bg2 dxe4 {6... Nf6 would transpose to 
7... b6 lines covered in the *Main Line French* chapter of the main KIA course.} 
7. Nxe4 ({I like this active approach. After} 7. dxe4 Ba6 {it would be harder 
for White to maintain control over the position.}) Bb7 8. Bf4 $1 Be7 9. Ne5 $1 
{[%cal Rg8f6,Ge4f6,Gg2c6][%csl Rc6,Re8] It is important to play this before 
castling. If Black manages to play ... Nf6 without being disturbed, then he 
won't have too many issues. Note that Nxc6 followed by Nd6+ is an immediate 
threat.} Nxe5 10. Bxe5 {[%cal Gg2b7,Ge5h8][%csl Re8,Ge4,Ge5,Gg2] White will 
castle next while Black has problems with finishing development.} Kf8 {[%csl 
Rf8] A sad necessity.} 11. O-O {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5]} Qd5 {[%cal Gd5g2] What 
else?} 12. f4 $1 {This is an excellent attacking move. We don't fear ... f5.} f5 
$6 {[%csl Re4]} 13. Bf3 $1 {Provoking Black to take on e4.} fxe4 $2 {This 
objectively loses but something like 13... Qd7 would be very sad. Black's 
position would be full of holes.} 14. Bxe4 {[%cal Ge4b7,Gf4f5,Gf1f8,Gd1h5][%csl 
Rf8,Ge5,Ge4,Gf1,Gd1]} Qd7 15. f5 {[%cal Gf5e6,Gf1f8][%csl Rf8,Rd7]} Nf6 16. fxe6 
{[%cal Ge4b7,Rd7e6][%csl Ge6]} Qc8 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. Qh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5f7][%csl 
Rf8] The only move but now White is completely winning.} Bd8 {It looks like 
Black is holding but here comes a nasty surprise.} 19. Bd6+ Kg8 20. Qe8+ $1 
{[%cal Gf1f8][%csl Rg8]} Nxe8 21. Rf8# {A picturesque position.} *

