[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598783"]

1. e4 e6 {The French Defence is the 3rd most popular opening against 1. e4. When 
I think about the King's Indian Attack - KIA - after 1. e4, it is this opening 
that comes into my mind. The great Bobby Fischer played a few games vs that 
tough-to-crack defence scoring remarkable victories. I decided that it is worth 
starting with 1... e6 so here we go.} 2. d3 $1 ({Of course, if you want to play 
the KIA, you need to start with this move.} 2. g3 $6 d5 {and White doesn't have 
time for} 3. d3 {due to} 3... dxe4 {and Black will get Queens off the board - it 
is not what we want.}) d5 {A 'French' move. 2... c5 would transpose to the Qe2 
vs e6 Sicilian lines *#8* or *#9*.} 3. Nd2 ({Just in time. Now, if Black decides 
to go for} 3. Nd2 3... dxe4 {we can safely play} 4. dxe4 {and the Knight on d2 
is very useful.}) c5 4. Ngf3 {White develops the Knight on the most natural 
square and will play g2-g3 next.} Nc6 (4... Bd6 5. g3 Nc6) {transposes to the 
4...Nc6 5. g3 Bd6 line.} 5. g3 Bd6 {I decided to look at this position - which 
may also be reached via a Sicilian move order - in this chapter because our 
Knight is already committed to d2 while in the Sicilian we have additional 
options.} 6. Bg2 Nge7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 ({A traditional way of handling this 
variation. Let me inform you that} 8. Nh4 $5 {with the plan of going f2-f4 is 
also an interesting option.}) Qc7 9. c3 {A start of one of the most typical 
plans associated with the KIA.} Bd7 10. a3 {White wants to expand on the 
queenside with b2-b4. It is better for Black to let us proceed with our idea 
because stopping it with ... a5 will have unpleasant consequences.} a5 11. a4 
{[%cal Bd2b1,Bb1a3,Ba3b5] We gain eternal control over the b5-square and we will 
land our Knight there with the ♘d2-b1-a3-b5 manoeuvre. Note that if our Knight 
would stay on b1 as in Sicilians we would be able to save two tempos.} ({I want 
to mention that} 11. d4 $5) {is also an interesting plan with the idea of 
playing e4-e5 and attacking on the kingside. Just remember not to combine both 
a4 and d4 because then the b4-square would be mortally weakened.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
