[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598784"]

1. e4 e6 2. d3 d5 {A 'French' move. 2... c5 would transpose to the Qe2 vs e6 
Sicilian lines *#8* or *#9*.} 3. Nd2 c5 {Let's focus on the main line of the KIA 
vs the French Defence. This is the variation that you will usually face when 
playing against the French Defence.} 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O b6 
{This is the 2nd most popular move after 7... O-O. Black's idea is to provoke 
White into playing e4-e5 and then he will happily castle long.} 8. Re1 $1 ({We 
would play this sooner or later so it is better to stick to it now. It is a 
useful waiting move. Note that} 8. e5 $6 {would be premature due to} 8... Nd7 9. 
Re1 Qc7 10. Qe2 Bb7 {followed by long castling.}) {Black will be able to attack 
us on the kingside with moves such as ...g5 or ...h5. Also, White's score in 
this line isn't particularly convincing so 8. Re1 is our move!} Bb7 9. a3 {I 
really like this little move. We want to get our standard plan of going c2-c3 + 
a2-a3 forcing through b2-b4 but I think it is necessary to start with a3.} (9. 
c3 {allows Black to change his plans completely and play} 9... O-O {after which} 
10. e5 Nd7 11. Nf1 b5 12. h4 {is not that effective because Black can play} 
12... b4 {.}) {The pawn on c3 is a hook for Black's queenside actions and in the 
main line after 7... O-O we rarely play c3. That's why I prefer 9. a3 to see 
Black's idea.} Qc7 10. c3 ({There is also an interesting line for reversed KID 
lovers.} 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nc4 {with a typical reversed KID position.}) ({Note 
that after} 10. exd5 {Black can't play} exd5 $6 {due to} 11. b4 $1 {and now} 
cxb4 $6 {is bad for Black after} 12. axb4 Nxb4 13. Ba3 O-O 14. Rxe7 Qxe7 15. c3 
{with a big advantage for White.}) ({After} 10. exd5 exd5 $6 11. b4 {the only 
chance for Black would be} 11... O-O {but} 12. bxc5 bxc5 13. Rb1 {guarantees 
White a small edge.}) {I give you this line as an alternative if you like 
positions arising after exd5 Nxd5.} O-O-O {Black evacuates his King to the 
queenside and will try to look for safety there. Things aren't that easy 
though!} 11. Qe2 {[%cal Bb2b4] Firstly, stepping away from the d-file and 
bolstering the centre.} h6 12. b4 $1 {[%cal Bb4c5,Ba1b1] Secondly, striking at 
Black's King.} g5 {Trying to compete in a race with us won't be successful for 
Black. In this position, we have a McLaren while Black drives a Dacia.} 13. bxc5 
Bxc5 (13... bxc5 {only opens the b-file for our Rook and after} 14. Rb1 {we have 
excellent prospects.}) 14. Nb3 {[%cal Ba3a4,Ba4a5] With *a3-a4-a5* being one 
idea.} Be7 15. exd5 {I think it is useful to open up the centre. Our pieces are 
very well mobilized and our Rook gets the e-file for itself.} Nxd5 16. Bb2 
{[%cal Bd3d4,Bc3c4,Bd4d5,Gb2h8][%csl Rc8] White has a huge advantage. One plan 
is to start an avalanche by playing c3-c4 followed by *d3-d4-d5* etc.} *

