1. e4 e6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 c5 {Let's focus on the main line of the KIA vs the 
French Defence. This is the variation that you will usually face when playing 
against the French Defence.} 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 
{It is useful to include this move before committing to e4-e5. It won't run away 
and Black has a decision to make.} Qc7 {I think that Black shouldn't play this 
way. His Queen will be misplaced on c7 and it won't contribute to his queenside 
offensive.} 9. e5 Nd7 10. Qe2 b5 11. Nf1 {A standard plan in practice!. White 
will play h2-h4 followed by *Nh2-g4* and *h4-h5-h6*.} a5 12. Bf4 a4 {[%cal 
Ba4a3]} 13. a3 $1 {[%cal Ra4a3,Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Bf1h2,Bh2g4] This is important. 
We can't let Black force through the ...a4-a3 push because we would be too weak 
on the dark squares. The great Fischer found this out over 50 years ago!} b4 14. 
h4 bxa3 15. bxa3 Ba6 16. h5 {[%cal Bf1h2,Bh2g4,Bh5h6] White built up a nice 
attacking position on the kingside. Check *Yuferov - Zakharov, Moscow 1995* 
which is analysed in the main KIA course to see how to proceed.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
