1. e4 e6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 c5 {Let's focus on the main line of the KIA vs the 
French Defence. This is the variation that you will usually face when playing 
against the French Defence.} 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 
{It is useful to include this move before committing to e4-e5. It won't run away 
and Black has a decision to make.} b5 {The most popular move. Black starts 
immediate counterplay on the queenside.} 9. e5 ({The option that I have a huge 
fondness for is} 9. exd5 {. It is not in style of the real KIA but the resulting 
positions are to my personal taste.} 9... exd5 {allows White to carry through} 
10. a4 b4 11. d4 {and now Black can't play} 11... c4 $2 {due to} 12. Ne5 Nxd4 
13. Ndxc4 {with a big advantage for White.}) ({I think that after} 9. exd5 
{Black has to play} 9... Nxd5 {and after} 10. a4 b4 11. Nc4 {we have an 
interesting version of reversed KID positions.}) {It is up to you - dear reader 
- which option you will choose. I suppose most players will stick to the main 
line with 9. e5 but KID aficionados may prefer 9. exd5.} Nd7 10. Nf1 {[%cal 
Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Bf1h2,Bh2g4,Gc1f4] I think that we all know what comes next. 
White will continue with h2-h4 followed by *N1h2-g4* and *h4-h5-h6*.} a5 11. h4 
b4 12. Bf4 {[%cal Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Bf1h2,Bh2g4] This is a starting position of the 
standard KIA vs the French Defence. I want to share with you two things: 1) 
White's results in practice are excellent; 2) Engine's evaluations may be 
misleading. The thing about engines is that they underestimate White's attacking 
chances on the kingside. The same thing happens in the classical lines of the 
King's Indian Defence. I saw many cases when the engine gave 'a winning 
advantage' for White but after a few moves, it changed it to a winning advantage 
for Black. Black's defensive task is not easy at all. White's plans of storming 
the kingside are clear: *Nf1-h2-g4* or *Nf1-e3-g4* - the Ne3 route is especially 
useful when Black's Queen is on c7. Then Nxd5 ideas are very effective - see 
*Plichta - Sliwerski* from 'My KIA games' chapter to see what I mean. White's 
other plan includes pushing the h-pawn up the board to force weaknesses on the 
dark squares. Black may stop this plan by playing ...h7-h6 but then he has to be 
ready for sacrifices on h6.} a4 {[%cal Ba4a3,Rb2b3][%csl Rb2,Rc3]} 13. a3 $1 
{[%cal Ra4a3] Once again I will mention that this is a necessary move.} bxa3 14. 
bxa3 Ba6 15. N1h2 {[%cal Bh2g4,Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Yd1h5,Yf3g5] I recommend looking at 
the *Kaidanov - Nijboer, Elista 1998* game which is analysed in the main KIA 
course to take a closer look at White's attacking plans.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "#6"]
[Black "6...e5 Reversed Botvinnik Sicilian"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598788"]

1. e4 c5 {The most popular of Black's responses to 1. e4. By playing the 
Sicilian Black is ready for tactical fireworks and long theoretical lines. It is 
beneficial to have the KIA ready whenever facing these players. Please note that 
the resulting positions will quite often transpose to the French lines.} 2. Nf3 
{It is useful to include this move before committing to d3 or g3. Please note 
that the resulting position can also be reached via the 1. Nf3 c5 2. e4 move 
order.} Nc6 {We will take a look at Black's lines connected with 2... Nc6 and 
2... d6. After 2... e6 I will recommend a specific setup connected with a quick 
Qe2. You can check my analysis of that line in the *#8* and *#9* lines. I want 
to mention that lines with 2... g6 will transpose to either 2... d6 or 2... Nc6 
- or even sometimes to the lines with ...e6 ...d5 and ...Nge7/...Nf6. I didn't 
analyse variations such as 2... a6 or 2... Nf6 - you can use the same setup 
against all of them and they will transpose one to another sooner or later.} 3. 
d3 ({If you want to play the} 3. g3 {move order you have to be prepared to meet} 
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qe6+ 6. Be2 {.}) {If the resulting position looks 
interesting to you, then I recommend taking a look at GM Munoz's games.} g6 
(3... Nf6 4. g3 d5 5. exd5 {transposes to the Reversed KID chapter.}) 4. g3 Bg7 
5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O e5 {This setup is also possible and frankly quite popular. 
Black clamps on the centre and in some cases will try to force through the 
...d6-d5 break. Also plans connected with ...f5 or ...b5 are possible.} 7. Nc3 
$5 {Personally, I really like this setup. White abandons his usual c3 + a3 + b4 
ideas and focuses on planting the Knight on d5. Note that the d5-square has been 
mortally weakened and White swifts his attention to that point of the board.} 
({That being said, White can also play stereotypically by} 7. c3 Nge7 8. a3 O-O 
9. b4 h6 10. Nbd2 Be6 11. Nb3 c4 12. dxc4 Bxc4 13. Re1 {with a complicated 
battle ahead.}) Nge7 8. Nd2 $1 {White will increase his control over the centre 
with Nc4 to come next. Moving the Knight helped to increase the scope of our 
light-squared Bishop. True, it is behind the e-pawn at the moment, but it 
secures the d5-outpost for the other Knight. Let me tell you that this setup was 
used by Mr Carlsen himself a couple of times.} O-O 9. Nc4 Be6 10. Nd5 ({Just in 
time.} 10. a4 {would allow Black to play} 10... d5 {.}) {White will play a2-a4 
next followed by c2-c3 when our pieces and pawns take away all of the critical 
squares from our opponent's pieces.} f5 11. f4 {Fighting back.} Qd7 ({Black 
shouldn't reduce tension in the centre.} 11... exf4 {runs into} 12. Bxf4 {with 
pressure on the d-pawn}) ({while} 11... fxe4 {allows White to open the d-file 
with} 12. dxe4 {in both cases with a nice advantage for White.}) 12. c3 Rae8 13. 
a4 {[%cal Yd1a4,Ba4a5,Bd1b3] I really like our control over the position. A plan 
that I like is a4-a5 followed by Qb3 or Qa4.} *

