[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598790"]

1. e4 c5 {The most popular of Black's responses to 1. e4. By playing the 
Sicilian Black is ready for tactical fireworks and long theoretical lines. It is 
very useful to have the KIA ready whenever facing these players. Please note 
that the resulting positions will quite often transpose to the French lines.} 2. 
Nf3 {It is useful to include this move before committing to d3 or g3. Please 
note that the resulting position can be also reached via the 1. Nf3 c5 2. e4 
move order.} Nc6 {We will take a look at Black's lines connected with 2... Nc6 
and 2... d6. After 2... e6 I will recommend a specific setup connected with a 
quick Qe2. You can check my analysis of that line in the #8 and #9 lines. I want 
to mention that lines with 2... g6 will transpose to either 2... d6 or 2... Nc6 
- or even sometimes to the lines with ...e6 ...d5 and ...Nge7/...Nf6. I didn't 
analyse variations such as 2... a6 or 2... Nf6 - you can use the same setup 
against all of them and they will transpose one to another sooner or later.} 3. 
d3 ({If you want to play the} 3. g3 {move order you have to be prepared to meet} 
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qe6+ 6. Be2 {.}) {If the resulting position looks 
interesting to you, then I recommend taking a look at GM Munoz's games.} g6 
(3... Nf6 4. g3 d5 5. exd5 {transposes to the Reversed KID lines *#10 - #12*.}) 
4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O Nf6 {This is one of the positions that you will reach 
quite often. Black plays the reversed English being a tempo down. It is 
important because we will use that tempo against Black.} 7. c3 {[%cal 
Bf1e1,Bd3d4] This is a favourite of mine. There are also moves such as 7. Nbd2 
or 7. h3, but I choose this system to be our main line.} ({Note that} 7. h3 
{allows Black to go} 7... e5) {followed by ... Be6 and ...Qd7 so I wouldn't 
recommend that.} O-O 8. Re1 {[%cal Bd3d4] Our KIA hero, Mr Amin Bassem played a 
lot of games with this system. White prepares a quick d3-d4 to increase control 
over the centre.} Bg4 {This stops d3-d4 but forces Black to part with his 
light-squared Bishop.} 9. h3 ({Now} 9. d4 $2 {would be a mistake due to} 9... 
cxd4 10. cxd4 Qb6 {and Black exerts annoying pressure on our position.}) ({If 
you would like to recapture on f3 with the Knight then} 9. Nbd2 {may be 
interesting for you.}) Bxf3 10. Qxf3 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2] Both recaptures are 
possible, but Amin always recaptures with a Queen. This is a little trick when 
working on an opening repertoire. You pick a model player who is rated 2700+ and 
look at his games. You can safely build up a repertoire relying on his 
variations because being that strong he for sure analysed them. This approach 
saves a lot of time.} Rb8 11. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4]} Nd7 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (11... b5 
{allows} 12. d4) 12. a4 {[%cal Rb7b5] This is a typical way of dealing with the 
...b5 threat. If Black wants to stick to his plan of going for ...b5, he needs 
to play ...a6 followed by ...b5. We can meet this with axb5, opening the a-file 
for our Rook. In the KIA, we keep our Rook on a1 quite often, because in certain 
cases it will activate itself without moving.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 13. Qd1 {[%cal 
Gf2f4,Gh3h4,Gd3d4] Preparing either d3-d4 or f2-f4, or even h3-h4.} b5 {By 
choosing this move order we are granted an additional possibility.} 14. axb5 
{[%cal Ga1a8]} axb5 15. e5 {[%cal Rc6e5,Rd7e5,Gf2f4][%csl Ge3,Gg2] This is the 
additional option that we get. Black can't take the pawn with either of his 
Knights because f2-f4 will be crushing.} *

