[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598791"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 Nc6 (3... d5 4. Qe2 {leads to the same thing.}) 4. g3 
d5 5. Qe2 $5 {This approach is the most effective when Black is committed to 
...d5. We postpone Nbd2 in favour of a Queen move because sometimes our 
queenside Knight may jump into c3. If you are fine with the French positions, 
then 5. Nbd2 transposes directly to the French lines #1 - #5 of this repertoire. 
Our basic idea is to play Bg2, castle and then decide what to do. If Black 
castles, then our plan is to play e4-e5 followed up by c2-c4.} Nf6 ({The most 
popular move.} 5... Be7 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O {transposes to the main position.}) 6. 
Bg2 Be7 7. O-O b6 {Postponing castling doesn't impress that much here compared 
to the French Main Line.} 8. e5 {[%cal Bc2c4,Bb1c3] We can break the rule of not 
playing e4-e5 before Black castles because we will strike in the centre first. 
Only after that, we will focus on the Black King.} Nd7 9. c4 $1 dxc4 $6 {Opening 
the d-file can't serve Black too well.} 10. dxc4 {[%cal Bf1d1,Gd1d8,Bb1c3] 
Followed up by Rd1 with a nagging pressure on the d-file.} Bb7 11. Nc3 {[%cal 
Rd8c7,Gc3b5]} a6 {[%cal Rc3b5] Black has to play this move to complete 
development. Otherwise, ...Qc7 would run into Nb5.} 12. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8]} Qc7 
13. Bf4 {White threatens Nd5! or Ne4.} O-O-O $2 14. Nd5 {See details of *Czekhov 
- Krasenkow, POL-chT 1994*, which is analysed in the main KIA course.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
