[White "#9 Qe2"]
[Black "2...e6 Sicilian b)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598792"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 Nc6 (3... d5 4. Qe2 {leads to the same thing.}) 4. g3 
d5 5. Qe2 $5 {This approach is the most effective when Black is committed to 
...d5. We postpone Nbd2 in favour of a Queen move because sometimes our 
queenside Knight may jump into c3. If you are fine with the French positions, 
then 5. Nbd2 transposes directly to the French lines of this repertoire. Our 
basic idea is to play Bg2, castle and then decide what to do. If Black castles, 
then our plan A is to play e4-e5 followed up by c2-c4.} Nf6 ({The most popular 
move.} 5... Be7 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O {transposes to the main position.}) 6. Bg2 Be7 
7. O-O O-O 8. e5 {The same plan as in the French Defence lines, that you could 
see at the beginning of this course.} Nd7 {The most typical continuation.} 9. c4 
$1 {This is White's most significant idea behind the Qe2 move order. White's 
score after this move is 65.5%, which indicates how huge practical problems it 
poses for Black.} Nb6 {Nearly as popular as 9...d4.} 10. b3 $1 {I like this move 
the most. White bolsters the c4-pawn and is ready to focus on the kingside.} 
({Note that} 10. Nc3 $6 {would be inaccurate due to} 10... Nd4 $1 {with mutual 
chances.}) a5 11. a4 {[%cal Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bh5h6,Bc1f4,Ra5a4,Rc5c4] Closing the 
queenside. Now, White can fully concentrate on the kingside. I think that this 
position is a positional nightmare for Black. He is left without any 
counterplay, while our plans are rather easy to guess - h4 + Bf4 + bringing 
minor pieces to the kingside. See *Ehlvest - Stripunsky*, which is analysed in 
the main KIA course for more instructions.} *

