[Black "6...g6 Reversed KID a)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598794"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d3 Nf6 4. g3 d5 5. exd5 {This is my personal favourite. I 
prefer to keep my Knight on b1 to stay more flexible. We will take on d5 sooner 
or later and I like to do it on the first possible occasion.} Nxd5 6. Bg2 g6 
{The most popular move. Black solidifies his kingside and prepares to develop 
the Bishop on the long diagonal.} 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. c3 {We can reach this 
position via many different transpositions.} b6 {Waiting with ...e5 and 
finishing development of the queenside.} 10. Nbd2 e5 11. Nc4 Re8 12. Ng5 {[%cal 
Gd1f3,Gf3f7,Gf3d5,Yg5e4,Ye4d6] It may look like a shot in the dark, but it is a 
result of a very dynamic plan. White may play Qf3 with a double threat to f7 and 
d5. Also, *Ng5-e4-d6* looks very tempting.} f6 $2 {The most popular move but a 
big mistake!} 13. Qa4 $1 {This is why I love this system! We can fully use the 
power of our active pieces.} Bb7 14. Ne4 {So now the d6-square is a problem for 
Black.} Re6 {Every other move allows Ned6 with a devastating effect.} (14... Bf8 
$2 {is one of them and White wins after} 15. Ned6 $1) 15. Qb3 {[%cal 
Ge4d6,Gc4d6,Yc4e3,Yg2h3] Renewing a threat of Ned6/ Ncd6 while keeping in mind 
ideas such as Bh3 and Ne3. White is much better.} Ba6 {There is nothing else.} 
16. Bh3 f5 17. Ng5 $1 {I am in love with this line! Tactics everywhere!} Re8 18. 
Bg2 $1 {[%cal Gc4d6] Calmly stepping back and - once again - threatening Nd6!.} 
Bxc4 (18... h6 19. Nd6 $1 $16) 19. Qxc4 Nce7 20. Qh4 $1 {White has many moves at 
his disposal, but I like this active operation the most. We force another 
weakness in Black's position.} h5 21. Qc4 {[%cal Ba2a4,Bf2f4][%csl Rg8,Gc4] And 
calmly back. White will increase pressure with a2-a4 and f2-f4. White is on the 
verge of victory.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "#12"]
[Black "6...g6 Reversed KID b)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598795"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d3 Nf6 4. g3 d5 5. exd5 {This is my personal favourite. I 
prefer to keep my Knight on b1 to stay more flexible. We will take on d5 sooner 
or later, and I like to do it on the first possible occasion.} Nxd5 6. Bg2 g6 
{The most popular move. Black solidifies his kingside and prepares to develop 
the Bishop on the long diagonal.} 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. c3 {We can reach this 
position via many different transpositions.} e5 {The most popular move building 
an impressive centre. I have to tell you a secret. I have a huge fondness for 
this pawn structure. I love playing it with White, and I also play a similar 
setup using the KID with Black.} 10. Nbd2 Re8 {This way of playing is risky as 
you've probably noticed.} 11. Ng5 $1 {Using the absence of the pawn on h6.} Nxc3 
{Winning a pawn, but White will have excellent compensation for it.} 12. bxc3 
Qxg5 13. Ne4 Qe7 {Trying to hold on to the pawn.} 14. Bg5 $1 Qc7 (14... f6 
{doesn't help due to} 15. Be3 b6 16. Nxc5 {and Black loses the c-pawn anyway.}) 
15. Nxc5 $14 {[%cal Bd1a4,Ba4h4,Yc5e4,Ye4f6,Ga1b1] White has ideas such as 
*Qa4-h4* and *Ne4-f6*, while Rb1 is always useful. I will show you one pitfall 
that Black may fall into.} b6 $4 16. Qa4 $18 {[%csl Rc6] This tactic works quite 
often with our Knight on c5.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "#13"]
[Black "3...dxe4 Caro-Kann"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598796"]

1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann. Black's setup is considered as one of the most solid 
ones.} 2. d3 {This is the standard way of employing the King's Indian Attack. We 
can use it here too but compared to French or Sicilian, I consider it to be less 
threatening for Black. In the #13 - #15 lines, we will take a look at all of 
Black's alternatives to 3... e5 which will be analysed in the #16 - #20 lines.} 
d5 3. Nd2 {This is a necessary move to reach our desired KIA setup. There is one 
funny thing that I once heard about Caro-Kann. Most of the players who use 
Caro-Kann as their primary weapon are so used to having positions with a little 
amount of space, that whenever they seize the centre, they feel uncomfortable. I 
guess that this is a half-joke and half-true, but there has to be something 
about that! At least let's hope so.} dxe4 {As in the French Defence, this limp 
move can't be good.} 4. dxe4 e5 5. Ngf3 Bc5 $2 {This move was played even by 
strong players. I can see 90 games in my database that went this way. Good for 
us because 5... Bc5 is a blunder.} 6. Nxe5 $1 Bxf2+ 7. Kxf2 Qd4+ 8. Ke1 Qxe5 9. 
Nc4 $1 {This move guarantees us an almost winning advantage.} Qxe4+ 10. Be2 (10. 
Kf2 {may be even stronger, but it unnecessarily complicates our lives.}) Qe6 11. 
Nd6+ {Rf1 will come next. Remember that we can't castle anymore.} Ke7 12. Rf1 
{[%cal Re6d6,Gf1f7]} Nf6 13. Nf5+ {[%cal Re7e8,Gf5g7]} Kf8 14. Qd8+ Ne8 15. Nd4 
Qe4 ({There is an enterprising line that goes} 15... Qd7 16. Bc4 Qxd8 17. Rxf7+ 
Kg8 18. Rd7+ Kf8 19. Ne6+ Kg8 20. Nxd8+ Kf8 21. Rf7+ Kg8 22. Rf6+ Be6 23. Bxe6#) 
16. Qxc8 Qxd4 17. Qxb7 {[%csl Ra8] Black loses the Rook and the game.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "#14"]
[Black "3...g6 Caro-Kann a)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598797"]

1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann. Black's setup is considered as one of the most solid 
ones.} 2. d3 {This is the standard way of employing the King's Indian Attack. We 
can use it here too but compared to French or Sicilian I consider it to be less 
threatening for Black. In the #13 - #15 lines, we will take a look at all of 
Black's alternatives to 3... e5 which will be analysed in the #16 - #20 lines.} 
d5 3. Nd2 {A necessary move to reach our desired KIA setup. There is one funny 
thing that I once heard about Caro-Kann. Most of the players who use Caro-Kann 
as their main weapon are so used to having positions with small amount of space, 
that whenever they seize the centre, they feel uncomfortable. I guess that this 
is a half-joke and half-true but there has to be something about that! At least 
let's hope so.} g6 {As I've mentioned in the beginning, we take care of all of 
Black's alternatives to the 3... e5 line first.} 4. Ngf3 Bg7 5. g3 e5 6. Bg2 Ne7 
{6... Nf6 would be desirable but it loses a pawn on e5.} 7. O-O O-O 8. b4 {I 
remember that in one of the books about King's Indian, the author gave ... b5 
for Black in a similar position with colours reversed. I immediately loved that 
idea and started using it on my own. White gains space on the queenside and 
prepares Bb2.} ({Let me tell you why I don't like the most popular continuation 
in this position, which is} 8. Re1 {. After} 8... d4 {we are forced to play some 
kind of reversed KID position but I don't like the fact that our Rook is on 
e1.}) {From f1 it may prepare f2-f4 break, but it requires losing two tempos to 
go back to f1. Let me show you two short lines to show you my doubts.} (8. Re1 
d4 9. Nc4 {allows} 9... b5 {and} 10. Ncxe5 {runs into} 10... f6 {.}) {If we need 
to retreat after 9... b5 it indicates that something went wrong.} ({The other 
line that I don't like is} 8. Re1 d4 9. a4 c5 10. Nc4 Nbc6 {and Black managed to 
get all of his needed moves. This is a reversed KID position but outside of this 
repertoire and also not to my taste.}) a5 {Trying to punish immediately White is 
critical.} 9. Bb2 (9. bxa5 {is around ten times more popular than my 
recommendation, but there is one specific line that I don't like for White.} 
9... Qxa5 10. Bb2 d4 11. a4 Qc7 12. c3 dxc3 13. Bxc3 Rd8 14. Nc4 Be6 15. Qc2 
Bxc4 16. dxc4 c5 {and I am not sure if White's Bishops are better than Black's 
Knights.}) {If you, however, want to stick to bxa5, then I recommend going 
through games of GM Sergei Tiviakov.} axb4 10. Bxe5 Bxe5 11. Nxe5 {[%csl 
Gd3,Ge4] We managed to win a central pawn for a flank one. It is far from an 
obvious advantage for us, but I think it is an improvement.} *

