1. e4 c6 {The Caro-Kann. Black's setup is considered as one of the most solid 
ones.} 2. d3 {This is the standard way of employing the King's Indian Attack. We 
can use it here too but compared to French or Sicilian I consider it to be less 
threatening for Black. In the #13 - #15 lines, we will take a look at all of 
Black's alternatives to 3... e5 which will be analysed in the #16 - #20 lines.} 
d5 3. Nd2 {A necessary move to reach our desired KIA setup. There is one funny 
thing that I once heard about Caro-Kann. Most of the players who use Caro-Kann 
as their main weapon are so used to having positions with small amount of space, 
that whenever they seize the centre, they feel uncomfortable. I guess that this 
is a half-joke and half-true but there has to be something about that! At least 
let's hope so.} g6 {As I mentioned in the beginning, we take care of all of 
Black's alternatives to the 3... e5 line first.} 4. Ngf3 Bg7 5. g3 e5 6. Bg2 Ne7 
{6... Nf6 would be desirable but it loses a pawn on e5.} 7. O-O O-O 8. b4 {I 
remember that in one of the books about King's Indian the author gave ...b5 for 
Black in a similar position with colours reversed. I immediately loved that idea 
and started using it on my own. White gains space on the queenside and prepares 
Bb2.} ({Let me tell you why I don't like the most popular continuation in this 
position which is} 8. Re1 {. After} 8... d4 {we are forced to play some kind of 
reversed KID position but I don't like the fact that our Rook is on e1.}) {From 
f1 it may prepare f2-f4 break but it requires losing two tempos to go back to 
f1. Let me show you two short lines to show you my doubts.} (8. Re1 d4 9. Nc4 
{allows} 9... b5 {and} 10. Nxe5 {runs into} 10... f6 {.}) {If we need to retreat 
after 9... b5 it indicates that something went wrong.} ({The other line that I 
don't like is} 8. Re1 d4 9. a4 c5 10. Nc4 Nbc6 {and Black managed to get all of 
his needed moves. This is a reversed KID position but outside of this repertoire 
and also not to my personal taste.}) a5 {Trying to immediately punish White is 
critical.} 9. Bb2 (9. bxa5 {is around 10 times more popular than my 
recommendation but there is one specific line that I don't like for White.} 9... 
Qxa5 10. Bb2 d4 11. a4 Qc7 12. c3 dxc3 13. Bxc3 Rd8 14. Nc4 Be6 15. Qc2 Bxc4 16. 
dxc4 c5 {and I am not sure if White's Bishops are better than Black's Knights.}) 
{If you, however, want to stick to bxa5, then I recommend going through games of 
GM Sergei Tiviakov.} d4 10. a3 axb4 11. axb4 Na6 12. c3 {[%cal 
Gf3e5,Gc3d4,Gb2e5][%csl Rd4,Re5]} dxc3 13. Bxc3 Qxd3 14. Bxe5 Be6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 
16. Qc1 {Once again, we managed to get a central pawn for a flank one. Also, the 
Black Knight is misplaced on a6, and our b4-pawn is of course taboo due to Qb2 
check. If you compare King's safety, it is evident that White's monarch is 
safer. All these aspects combined guarantee White at least a small edge.} *

