1. e4 c6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 e5 $1 {Now, we will take a look at the lines connected 
with 3... e5!. I give an exclamation mark to this move because I think that it 
objectively equalizes for Black.} 4. Ngf3 Nd7 $6 {Preparing ...Ngf6. It has a 
serious drawback though.} 5. d4 $1 {White wastes a tempo but at a powerful move. 
Black doesn't have an easy response to White's central strike.} dxe4 6. Nxe4 
Ngf6 {This doesn't work well for Black.} 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 8. Bg5 {White develops 
with tempo.} Qe6 9. dxe5 Bc5 ({Watch out for} 9... Nxe5 $4 10. Qd8# {.}) 10. Bf4 
f6 11. Bd3 $1 {[%cal Be1g1] Finishing development and planning to castle short.} 
Nxe5 (11... fxe5 $2 12. O-O $16) 12. Nxe5 fxe5 13. Bg3 e4 14. Qh5+ {[%cal 
Gh5c5]} g6 15. Qxc5 exd3+ 16. Be5 {[%csl Ge5,Rc8,Re8] Despite material equality, 
White is winning. Black won't be able to castle while White can choose between 
going short or long, followed by sending Rooks to the attack.} *

