[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598800"]

1. e4 c6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 e5 $1 {Now, we will take a look at the lines connected 
with 3... e5!. I give an exclamation mark to this move because I think that it 
objectively equalizes for Black.} 4. Ngf3 Bd6 {This is the critical 
continuation. I think that there are not many lines after 5. g3 that guarantees 
White an advantage, but I will do my best to present you - dear reader - the 
most exciting positions. So the goal of this chapter is to get dynamic play, not 
an advantage. There is simply no advantage for White here.} 5. g3 {Let's begin 
with taking a look at this traditional way of handling the King's Indian Attack. 
5.d4 will be analysed later.} f5 $5 6. exd5 (6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O O-O {and the most 
satisfactory option that I've found for White is} 8. b3 fxe4 9. dxe4 Qc7 10. Bb2 
{with a complicated position.}) {I think that 6. exd5 is stronger and guarantees 
White an advantage.} cxd5 7. c4 {Striking at Black's centre is a must.} d4 $6 
{Too slow. Black gets a Benoni being down a full tempo.} 8. Bg2 Nf6 9. O-O Nc6 
10. Re1 O-O 11. c5 {[%cal Rd6c5,Gf3e5] Always active! White strikes before Black 
manages to consolidate. Black can't take the pawn due to Nxe5 coming.} Bc7 12. 
b4 $16 {[%cal Bd2c4,Bd1b3,Gf3e5,Rc6b4,Gb4b5] White is much better. I can't see 
how Black wants to finish development while White can combine multiple plans 
such as b4-b5, Nc4 or Qb3.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "#18 Traditional 5.g3"]
[Black "4...Bd6 Caro-Kann"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598801"]

1. e4 c6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 e5 $1 {Now, we will take a look at the lines connected 
with 3... e5!. I give an exclamation mark to this move because I think that it 
objectively equalizes for Black.} 4. Ngf3 Bd6 {This is the critical 
continuation. I think that there are not many lines after 5. g3 that guarantees 
White an advantage but I will do my best to present you - dear reader - with the 
most interesting positions. So the goal of this chapter is to get dynamic play, 
not an advantage. There is simply no advantage for White here.} 5. g3 {Firstly, 
we will take a look at this traditional way of handling the King's Indian 
Attack.} Nf6 {By far the most popular move. It is also the most logical one as 
Black finished development of the kingside and prepares short castling.} 6. Bg2 
O-O 7. O-O Bg4 {Before committing to ...Re8 Black develops his light-squared 
Bishop.} 8. h3 Bh5 {[%cal Bb2b3,Yg3g4,Yf3h4]} 9. b3 {[%cal Bc1b2] This move is 
quite high scoring - 63%. If we compare it with 9. Re1 and 9. Qe1 it should set 
Black the most PRACTICAL problems.} ({That being said} 9. g4 $5 {is also 
possible. One possible scenario may be} 9... Bg6 10. Nh4 Nbd7 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. 
g5 Nh5 13. exd5 cxd5 14. Nb3 Nb6 15. a4 {Chigaev - Bluebaum, Aeroflot 2018. 
Black should improve on his play with} 15... a5 {.}) Nbd7 10. Bb2 Re8 11. Qe1 
{[%cal Bf3h4,Bh4f5] This is an interesting idea. White wants to play *Nh4-f5*, 
but first, he needs to step away from the d1-h5 diagonal.} a5 {[%cal Ba5a4]} 12. 
a3 {[%cal Ra5a4,Gb3b4]} (12. a4 $6) {would leave too many weaknesses on the 
queenside - especially the b4-square.} Qc7 13. Nh4 Rad8 14. Kh1 {White 
safeguards the King before going for any active operations.} b5 15. Nf5 Bf8 16. 
f4 $1 {Whenever you think that the position can't be more complicated, then the 
f-pawn shows itself.} dxe4 17. Nxe4 {Improving on two games that went 17. dxe4 
instead.} exf4 18. Rxf4 {[%cal Gb2g7,Be1f2,Ba1f1,Bf5h6][%csl Ge4,Gf4,Gf5] 
White's pieces are very active. We need to step away from the e-file with our 
Queen, probably by employing Qf2. Remember always to consider ideas connected 
with Nh6.} *

