1. e4 c6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 e5 4. Ngf3 Bd6 5. d4 $5 {We could see a similar central 
strike in the *#16 line*. White changes gears and tries to use the fact that the 
c-pawn blocks a natural developing square for the Black Knight and the d6-Bishop 
is prone to our Knight's jumps. Let me tell you that White scores 51.2% after 5. 
g3 and 56.4% for 5. d4. These numbers differ even more in my 2000+ database - 
49% for 5. g3 and 58% for 5. d4. Knowing these numbers, we can easily indicate 
that Black faces practical problems against 5. d4. I decided it is an exciting 
line that deserves to be analysed. Here we go.} exd4 ({Virtually the only move.} 
5... Nd7 {is weaker and would transpose to the *#16 variation*.}) 6. exd5 
{Clarifying the situation in the centre is the most reliable concept.} Nf6 {The 
other way of reaching the Isolated Queen's Pawn position but this time it will 
be the d4-pawn instead of the d5-one.} 7. dxc6 Nxc6 8. Be2 {White focuses on 
finishing development.} O-O 9. Nb3 ({Much less popular than} 9. O-O {, but it 
has a great point behind it. White stops Black from playing ...Bc7 due to the 
hanging pawn on d4. Our King is not under any immediate danger, and we can 
castle on the next move.}) Re8 10. O-O Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 {A more popular move than 
taking on f3 but I think that White can take the bull by its horns and grab the 
d-pawn.} 12. Nfxd4 $1 {But with this Knight! We need to exchange pieces for 
getting rid of some pressure.} Bxe2 13. Nxe2 Bh2+ 14. Kxh2 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Rxe2 
16. Rd2 {White is temporarily a pawn up and will try to hang on it.} Re1 $6 17. 
Nc5 {[%cal Bc5d3,Re1f1,Gg2g3,Gh2g2] With Nd3 to come next and the Black Rook has 
to abandon the 1st rank. If ...Rf1 then just g2-g3 followed by Kg2.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "#20 Modern 5.d4!?"]
[Black "4...Bd6 Caro-Kann b)"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598803"]

1. e4 c6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 e5 4. Ngf3 Bd6 5. d4 $5 {We could see a similar central 
strike in the #16 line. White changes gears and tries to use the fact that the 
c-pawn blocks a natural developing square for the Black Knight and the d6-Bishop 
is prone to our Knight's jumps. Let me tell you that White scores 51.2% after 5. 
g3 and 56.4% for 5. d4. These numbers differ even more in my 2000+ database - 
49% for 5. g3 and 58% for 5. d4. Knowing these numbers we can easily indicate 
that Black faces practical problems against 5. d4. I decided it is a very 
interesting line that deserves to be analysed. Here we go.} exd4 {Virtually the 
only move. 5... Nd7 is weaker and would transpose to the 4... Nd7 5. d4 Bd6 #16 
variation.} 6. exd5 {Clarifying situation in the centre is the strongest 
concept.} cxd5 {The most popular continuation. Black accepts the fact that he 
will play with an isolated pawn on d5. Note that by employing the Caro-Kann 
Defence, Black may not be familiar with different plans and subtleties of the 
Isolated Queen's Pawn positions.} 7. Nxd4 ({The choice of most top players. It 
was also possible to go for} 7. Bb5+ {, and it scores even better than the text 
move, but I am not a huge fan of the position after} 7... Nc6 $1 8. O-O Qb6 {.}) 
Nf6 $6 {I think that this is inaccurate and it is confirmed by White's score - 
69.6% after 8. Bb5+!} 8. Bb5+ $1 {Black should regret not having put his Knight 
on c6.} Bd7 9. Qe2+ {Creating some inconvenience in Black's position. Now he 
will suffer in a worse endgame with zero winning chances.} Be7 10. Nf5 Nc6 
{[%cal Rf5e7,Gc6d4]} 11. Bxc6 (11. Nxe7 {would be weaker due to} Nd4 {with 
counter chances.}) bxc6 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Qxe7+ Kxe7 14. Nb3 {[%cal 
Gc1e3,Gf2f3][%csl Gc5,Gd4,Rd5,Rc6,Ra7] Even though there are opposite coloured 
Bishops on the board, I would love to play this position with White. Black has 
three pawn islands and some squares in his camp are weak - especially c5 and d4. 
White will play f2-f3 followed by Kf2 and then Be3 with a more pleasant 
position. Check out the *Janosi - Shishkin* game, which is analysed in the main 
KIA course for more details.} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "#21 KIA"]
[Black "Alekhine"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4598805"]

1. e4 {In the *#21 - #26 lines*, we will take a look at Black's different 1st 
move options. A lot of them will very often transpose one to another. For 
example 1...g6 or 1... d6 can reach the Sicilian setup and 1... e5, 1... Nc6 and 
1... Nf6 should reach the same position too. Of course, some independent 
treatment is possible and it depends on Black how he is going to handle the 
position. That being said, I think that White can employ the KIA against any of 
Black's 1st moves except for 1... d5. Still, I think I managed to find a nice 
line for White, in which our play will be very similar to the other lines - 
especially from the *Reversed King's Indian Defence chapter*. There is one thing 
that I need to tell before we continue with further analysis. White's setup 
won't be as effective as against the French, Sicilian or Caro-Kann. The reason 
for that is that Black can easily claim the centre and follow it up by playing 
natural moves such as ...e5 ...Nf6 ...Nc6 ...Bc5 etc. I hesitated if I want to 
add this chapter or not but I think it is your choice if you want to employ the 
KIA against virtually any of Black's defences, or just stick to 1... e6 1... c5 
and 1... c6. But, if you insist on playing the King's Indian Attack against 
everything there is some good news. White won't ever be objectively worse in 
lines that I suggest. My job will be to present you with variations that lead to 
interesting positions and fill them with different plans for White. One more 
thing to point out is that if you have good lines against 1... g6 1... d6 1...e5 
etc, then you can safely use them and add the KIA whenever you want. and stick 
to your lines against variations from this chapter. After that lengthy 
introduction - let's proceed!} Nf6 {The Alekhine Defence. We can try our KIA 
here too.} 2. d3 ({I have to mention that objectively} 2. e5 {is the strongest 
move.}) d5 (2... e5 {is covered under the 1... e5 2... Nf6 move order,}) 
({while} 2... c5 3. Nf3 {leads to the Sicilian or the French chapter with one 
exception being} 3... d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 {when we've transposed 
directly to the Reversed King's Indian Chapter.}) {2... d5 keeps things more in 
the spirit of the Alekhine system when Black usually strikes with his d-pawn on 
the first occasion.} 3. exd5 (3. e5 {is once again probably the strongest, but 
if we decided not to do it on the 2nd move, then we shouldn't do it now. 3. exd5 
is my personal preference to try to reach the desired KIA setup.}) Nxd5 4. g3 
{Once again, many transpositions are possible.} g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O 
e5 8. Re1 Nc6 9. Nc3 {I think it is nice to attack Black in the centre 
immediately. The absence of a pawn on c5 eases the task.} Nxc3 10. bxc3 {[%cal 
Ba1b1] White strengthened his centre. We will play Rb1 next. I want to point out 
that the following line doesn't work for Black.} e4 $6 11. Rxe4 Bxc3 12. Rb1 
{[%cal Bc1a3,Bc1g5,Yd3d4][%csl Rc3] All of White's pieces are active, and the 
b1-Rook combined with the g2-Bishop put annoying pressure on Black's queenside. 
White may fancy playing Rc4 or even Rh4, but I would recommend sticking to Re1 - 
when our Rook is attacked - followed by Bg5. Also, moves such as Ba3, Bh6 or 
even d3-d4 trying to shut the Black Bishop out are worth considering.} *

