1. e4 {In the *#21 - #26 lines*, we will take a look at Black's different 1st 
move options. A lot of them will very often transpose one to another. For 
example 1...g6 or 1... d6 can reach the Sicilian setup and 1... e5, 1... Nc6 and 
1... Nf6 should reach the same position too. Of course, some independent 
treatment is possible and it depends on Black how he is going to handle the 
position. That being said, I think that White can employ the KIA against any of 
Black's 1st moves except for 1... d5. Still, I think I managed to find a nice 
line for White, in which our play will be very similar to the other lines - 
especially from the *Reversed King's Indian Defence chapter*. There is one thing 
that I need to tell before we continue with further analysis. White's setup 
won't be as effective as against the French, Sicilian or Caro-Kann. The reason 
for that is that Black can easily claim the centre and follow it up by playing 
natural moves such as ...e5 ...Nf6 ...Nc6 ...Bc5 etc. I hesitated if I want to 
add this chapter or not but I think it is your choice if you want to employ the 
KIA against virtually any of Black's defences, or just stick to 1... e6 1... c5 
and 1... c6. But, if you insist on playing the King's Indian Attack against 
everything there is some good news. White won't ever be objectively worse in 
lines that I suggest. My job will be to present you with variations that lead to 
interesting positions and fill them with different plans for White. One more 
thing to point out is that if you have good lines against 1... g6 1... d6 1...e5 
etc, then you can safely use them and add the KIA whenever you want. and stick 
to your lines against variations from this chapter. After that lengthy 
introduction - let's proceed!} e5 {All of Black's options connected with 
claiming the centre by ...e5 - on move 1, 2 or 3 will be analysed here. So under 
1... Nf6 or 1... Nc6 move order we will only look at original and independent 
ideas not connected with ...e5.} 2. Nf3 {It is also possible to start with 2. 
d3, and it would be slightly lighter in theory, but our move order provokes 
Black to play 2... f5 or 2... d5 which are bad for Black. Also, if we go 2. d3 
Black knows what we are doing and can adjust accordingly. After 2. Nf3 he still 
has a guessing game, and he needs to for a setup that he maybe would prefer to 
avoid after KIA.} f5 $2 {The Latvian Gambit. I think it is even worse than the 
Elephant Gambit.} 3. Nxe5 {The pawn has to be taken.} Qf6 {This continuation is 
twice as popular as all of the other alternatives combined. The fact that Black 
plays with the f-pawn and pushes his Queen again after only three moves 
indicates that White shouldn't have problems with getting a substantial 
advantage.} 4. d4 d6 5. Nc4 fxe4 6. Nc3 {Black's centre is already under severe 
pressure.} Qg6 7. f3 exf3 (7... Nf6 {doesn't help after} 8. fxe4 Nxe4 9. Qe2 Bf5 
10. Nd2 {.}) 8. Qxf3 Nc6 (8... Qxc2 $4 9. Bd3 {is not recommended for Black.}) 
9. d5 Nb4 10. Ne3 {[%csl Gg4,Gc2]} Nf6 11. a3 Na6 (11... Nxc2+ {is bad due to} 
12. Nxc2 Qxc2 13. Bd3 Qb3 14. Ne4) {threatening Nxf6+ followed by Bg6+ picking 
up the Black Queen.} 12. Bd3 Qh5 ({If} 12... Qf7 {then} 13. b4 {blocking Black's 
Knight.}) 13. Qxh5+ Nxh5 14. O-O {[%csl Ra6,Rh5] If you doubt that White has a 
huge advantage, then take a look at Black's pieces. None of them serves any 
useful purpose. Note that this is the best position that Black can get after 
entering the Latvian territory!} *

