1. e4 {In the *#21 - #26 lines*, we will take a look at Black's different 1st 
move options. A lot of them will very often transpose one to another. For 
example 1...g6 or 1... d6 can reach the Sicilian setup and 1... e5, 1... Nc6 and 
1... Nf6 should reach the same position too. Of course, some independent 
treatment is possible and it depends on Black how he is going to handle the 
position. That being said, I think that White can employ the KIA against any of 
Black's 1st moves except for 1... d5. Still, I think I managed to find a nice 
line for White, in which our play will be very similar to the other lines - 
especially from the *Reversed King's Indian Defence chapter*. There is one thing 
that I need to tell before we continue with further analysis. White's setup 
won't be as effective as against the French, Sicilian or Caro-Kann. The reason 
for that is that Black can easily claim the centre and follow it up by playing 
natural moves such as ...e5 ...Nf6 ...Nc6 ...Bc5 etc. I hesitated if I want to 
add this chapter or not but I think it is your choice if you want to employ the 
KIA against virtually any of Black's defences, or just stick to 1... e6 1... c5 
and 1... c6. But, if you insist on playing the King's Indian Attack against 
everything there is some good news. White won't ever be objectively worse in 
lines that I suggest. My job will be to present you with variations that lead to 
interesting positions and fill them with different plans for White. One more 
thing to point out is that if you have good lines against 1... g6 1... d6 1...e5 
etc, then you can safely use them and add the KIA whenever you want. and stick 
to your lines against variations from this chapter. After that lengthy 
introduction - let's proceed!} e5 {All of Black's options connected with 
claiming the centre by ...e5 - on move 1, 2 or 3 will be analysed here. So under 
1... Nf6 or 1... Nc6 move order we will only look at original and independent 
ideas not connected with ...e5.} 2. Nf3 {It is also possible to start with 2. 
d3, and it would be slightly lighter in theory, but our move order provokes 
Black to play 2... f5 or 2... d5 which are bad for Black. Also, if we go 2. d3 
Black knows what we are doing and can adjust accordingly. After 2. Nf3 he still 
has a guessing game, and he needs to for a setup that he maybe would prefer to 
avoid after KIA.} Nc6 {By far the most popular move. Black is definitely ready 
for the Ruy Lopez, Italian, Scotch etc. Is he ready for the King's Indian Attack 
though?} 3. d3 Nf6 {We can reach this position by different move orders. Black 
can choose 1... e5, 1... Nc6 or 1... Nf6.)} 4. g3 Bc5 {Black's most popular 
move. He develops and prepares ...d6 followed by ...O-O} 5. Bg2 d6 {5... O-O 
will transpose to 5... d6 if Black decides to go for ...d6 or to 4... d5 if he 
will push his d-pawn to d5.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 {I like this approach. White 
plans to play h2-h3 followed by Be3 with attacking chances on the kingside.} a6 
8. h3 {White plans to play Kh2 followed by Nh4.} h6 (8... Be6 9. Kh2 h6 {just 
transposes.}) 9. Kh2 Be6 10. Nh4 {My favourite plan for White. We want to attack 
on the kingside, but for the moment we threaten Nd5 after which Black wouldn't 
have any counterplay.} d5 {As I've mentioned if we manage to put our Knight on 
d5 Black would be in trouble. 10... d5 has to be played now.} 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. 
Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Qg4 $1 {Threatening Bxh6 and Nf5. Black has only one satisfactory 
response.} Be6 14. Qh5 {[%cal Gc1h6,Gg2e4,Gf2f4] We lured Black's Bishop to e6 
where it is less active, and we preserved our valuable Bishop on g2. White 
threatens Bxh6 with a crushing attack and if Black defends we can put more wood 
into the fire with Be4 and f2-f4. I think it is exactly the type of position 
that we should look in the King's Indian Attack!} *

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fischer, Robert James"]
[Black "Myagmarsuren, Lhamsuren"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4602801"]

1. e4 e6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. g3 c5 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Ngf3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. e5 
({Nowadays, it is considered best to start with} 8. Re1 {.}) Nd7 9. Re1 b5 10. 
Nf1 b4 11. h4 a5 12. Bf4 a4 13. a3 $1 {It was the first game that featured this 
move. White wants to avoid *...a4-a3* from Black. It would let Black weaken our 
queenside structure because *b2-b3 *would be forced. Black can then proceed with 
ideas like ...Nd4 to claim more dark squares on the queenside.} bxa3 {It looks 
correct to open up the queenside.} 14. bxa3 Na5 15. Ne3 {Fischer decided that he 
can reach the g4-square through the more active e3.} Ba6 16. Bh3 $6 ({White sees 
that Black reduced control over the e6-square by removing his Bishop from c8 
but} 16. Ng5 {followed by Qh5 was simple and strong. White's attack would be 
almost impossible to parry without material losses.}) d4 17. Nf1 (17. Ng4 {seems 
more thematic.}) Nb6 18. Ng5 Nd5 19. Bd2 (19. Qh5 {right away was possible and 
probably stronger.}) Bxg5 20. Bxg5 Qd7 21. Qh5 {White slowly brings his pieces 
to Black's King.} Rfc8 22. Nd2 (22. Nh2 $1 {with the familiar idea of Ng4 was 
simple and strong.}) Nc3 23. Bf6 $1 {[%csl Rg7] Setting up a deadly net which 
will strangle Black's King. Qg5 is an immediate threat.} Qe8 (23... gxf6 24. 
exf6 Kh8 25. Nf3 ({25.Bf5! exf5 26.Re7! may be even stronger. It is a line that 
the one and only Kingscrusher suggested to me!}) Nd5 26. Ne5 Nxf6 27. Qh6 Qe7 
28. Bxe6 {I am sure Fischer saw that when he decided on 23. Bf6!.}) 24. Ne4 $1 
{[%cal Ge4f6,Ge4g5,Ge4d6] Bringing more pieces into play. If Black takes on e4 
we recapture with the Rook and can consider Rg4 ideas.} g6 ({Black's last chance 
was} 24... Bb7 {but after} 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. Qg5+ {followed by Nd6 White's 
attack would be very strong.}) 25. Qg5 {[%cal Bh4h5]} Nxe4 26. Rxe4 c4 27. h5 
{[%cal Be4h4,Gh4h8][%csl Rg6] Very instructive. White uses his h-pawn to force 
more weaknesses while preparing Rh4. This is what we call a multipurpose move!} 
cxd3 28. Rh4 Ra7 29. Bg2 $3 {What an amazing move! White decides that he needs 
the light-squared Bishop to finish Black.} dxc2 30. Qh6 $1 {[%csl Rg7]} Qf8 31. 
Qxh7+ {[%cal Bh5g6,Bg2e4][%csl Rg8]} ({Black resigned. It is a shame because he 
didn't let Fischer demonstrate a beautiful idea} 31. Qxh7+ 31... Kxh7 32. hxg6+ 
Kxg6 33. Be4# {.}) {Crushing victories like this have convinced me to start 
employing the King's Indian Attack myself.} 1-0

[Event "Short & Sweet: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Site "Main Level"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fischer, Robert James"]
[Black "Ibrahimoglu, Ismet"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "Main Level"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-sweet-the-kings-indian-attack/course/27065, variation/4602800"]

{As you can see, Fischer used the King's Indian Attack not only against the 
French and Sicilian but against the Caro-Kann too.} 1. e4 c6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 g6 
4. Ngf3 Bg7 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 {In my opinion, 
White is already better. We were presented with a pair of Bishops for free, so I 
would be happy to get this position.} Nbd7 10. Qe2 {Preparing e4-e5 or f2-f4. 
Our Queen is perfectly placed on e2.} dxe4 $6 {As a rule of thumb, you shouldn't 
open up the position when your opponent has a pair of Bishops.} 11. dxe4 Qc7 12. 
a4 {Grabbing space on the queenside and preparing a4-a5 in some cases.} Rad8 13. 
Nb3 b6 14. Be3 {Black's queenside is already under serious pressure.} c5 15. a5 
e5 $6 {Weakening light squares everywhere. White is much better now. It is very 
educational to see how Fischer uses all of his positional trumps to destroy 
Black's position step by step.} 16. Nd2 Ne8 17. axb6 axb6 18. Nb1 $1 {[%cal 
Bb1c3][%csl Gb5,Gd5] This Knight has done its job. Now, it will be relocated to 
d5 or b5.} Qb7 19. Nc3 Nc7 20. Nb5 Qc6 21. Nxc7 Qxc7 22. Qb5 {All of White's 
plans are connected with the light squares. Our Bishop on g2 may look dumb but 
it will join the game via f1.} Ra8 23. c3 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4] Fischer doesn't rush. 
He knows that Black lacks counterplay, and he can slowly build up his plans.} 
Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Rb8 25. Ra6 Bf8 26. Bf1 $1 Kg7 27. Qa4 {White will put the Bishop 
on b5 followed by Ra7.} Rb7 28. Bb5 Nb8 29. Ra8 {Black's pieces are paralysed. 
White is positionally winning.} Bd6 30. Qd1 {Fischer decided to change targets 
and switches his attention to the h6-square.} Nc6 31. Qd2 ({The computer-like} 
31. Bh6+ Kxh6 32. Rg8 $3 {would end the game faster.}) h5 32. Bh6+ Kh7 33. Bg5 
{Threatening both Bf6 and Qd5.} Rb8 34. Rxb8 Nxb8 35. Bf6 Nc6 36. Qd5 Na7 37. 
Be8 {A complete triumph of White's strategy. Fischer's Bishops are monsters in 
this game. These types of monsters that were hiding under our beds when we were 
young...} Kg8 38. Bxf7+ Qxf7 39. Qxd6 {There was no point in continuing. Black's 
position completely collapsed. A superb performance by the legendary American.} 
1-0

